name: 1-methylimidazole-5-carboxaldehyde
Reason: To predict the melting point of 1-methylimidazole-5-carboxaldehyde, we start with the melting point of imidazole as the basic unit. Imidazole has a melting point around 90°C. The methyl group typically raises the melting point due to the increase in van der Waals forces from the added carbon and hydrogen atoms; however, this effect on melting point is less pronounced than its impact on boiling point. Estimating the effect of a methyl group could add roughly 5°C. The presence of a carboxaldehyde group (-C=O) generally has a larger impact on melting point due to its ability to participate in hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions, which could raise the melting point significantly. However, the conjugative effect of the aldehyde group with the imidazole ring system might have an electron delocalizing effect, leading to lesser intermolecular interactions than a typical aldehyde, potentially reducing this increase. Estimating conservatively, we could predict an increase of about 15-20°C for the addition of the aldehyde group. Combining these, we might expect an additive increase of 20-25°C compared to the base imidazole structure.
